fficient in sparse graphs. To address this, we usually use priority queues =
to manage the candidate vertices. This data structure allows for efficient =
retrieval of the vertex with the best evaluation, as well as quick insertio=
n of new ones.</p><p>However, for DFS and BFS, the evaluation functions are=
 simple enough that we can use basic data structures instead: a stack for D=
FS and a queue for BFS. This simplicity is one of the reasons these two alg=
orithms are so widely used and easy to implement.</p><p>This evaluation-fun=
ction framework can help you understand many search algorithms, including D=
